DATA CLOUD
Share Data with Snowflake Using Zero Copy Integration

To access Data Cloud data, create a data share that contains Data Cloud objects. You can access Data Cloud objects as views in a Snowflake account. When data is available in Snowflake, you can work on harmonized and unified data.

Before you begin:

Make sure that your Snowflake admin adds the Data Cloud IP Addresses to the allowlist.
Verify Snowflake Supported Regions for Data Cloud.

Data shares aren’t available when Snowflake is deployed behind private connectivity, such as AWS Private Link, Azure Private Link, or Google Cloud Private Service Connect.

Identify the Data Cloud objects you want to access and create a data share in Data Cloud.
For more information, see Create a Data Share.
Create users in Snowflake and obtain the user credentials.
For more information, see Get User Credentials from Snowflake.
To establish connectivity with a Snowflake account, create a data share target in Data Cloud.
For more information, see Create Data Share Target and Connect with Snowflake.
To make the Data Cloud objects accessible in Snowflake, link the data share with the data share target.
For more information, see Link or Unlink Data Shares and Data Share Targets.
View the data share in Snowflake.
Select the data share from private sharing in the Snowflake account.
Create a database on the data share.
To view the Data Cloud objects in the database login as an ACCOUNTADMIN. You can query the data and create joins across Data Cloud and Snowflake tables. If you’re using the classic console, the data shares are available on the Inbound tab.
Snowflake Supported Regions for Data Cloud
Data Cloud supports integration with Snowflake in these regions.
Get User Credentials from Snowflake
Gather the user information and authentication details in Snowflake to create a data share target.
Create Data Share Target and Connect with Snowflake
Create a data share target in Data Cloud to establish connectivity with a Snowflake account.
